---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { loadMapData } from '~/lib/loadMapData';

const data = await loadMapData(import.meta.env.BASE_URL);
const totalEntities = data.entities.length;
const totalFactions = data.factions.length;
---
<BaseLayout title="About">
  <article class="page prose">
    <h1>About MysterMap</h1>
    <p>
      A field guide to the United States, drawn by people who believe
      something else lives here too. {totalEntities} entities. {totalFactions} factions.
      Centuries of sightings. One interactive map.
    </p>

    <h2>What you're looking at</h2>
    <p>
      Every shaded territory on the home page is somewhere that lore
      says is — or was — under the sway of a supernatural faction. Click any
      territory to read the story. Drag the time slider to watch the map fill
      in across the centuries. Toggle factions to follow a single thread, like
      witches from Salem 1692 onward.
    </p>

    <h2>How it's built</h2>
    <p>
      A static Astro site. No database, no accounts. Faction descriptions live
      in YAML, entity profiles in Markdown, and territories in plain GeoJSON
      files — all in this repo. Adding a new cryptid is three files and a pull
      request.
    </p>

    <h2>Contribute</h2>
    <p>
      See <code>CONTRIBUTING.md</code> in the repository for the step-by-step
      walkthrough. The short version: copy <code>_template.md</code>, draw a
      polygon at <a href="https://geojson.io" rel="noopener">geojson.io</a>,
      drop in a Wikimedia Commons image with credit, open a PR.
    </p>

    <h2>Sources & disclaimers</h2>
    <p>
      Every entry cites at least one source. We treat folklore as folklore —
      this site documents what people have <em>said</em> about America's
      supernatural geography, not what is empirically true. Indigenous
      traditions are sketched lightly and with citations to Indigenous-led
      writing where available; corrections are welcome.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
